<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="specPoint"><h2 id="post-transcriptional-modification">Post-transcriptional Modification</h2><ul><li><p>Antibody molecules consist primarily of <b>protein</b></p></li><li><p>They contain four separate <span class="popovers" data-content="A polymer consisting of a large chain of amino acids bonded together by peptide bonds." data-title="Polypeptide" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">polypeptide</span> chains, two of which are longer, <b>heavy chains</b>, and two of which are shorter, <b>light chains</b></p></li><li><p>The structure of the heavy chain determines whether an antibody will be <b>bound to the membrane of a white blood cell</b>, or <b>secreted directly</b> into the blood</p></li><li><p>Some heavy chains contain an <b>extra section which allows the antibody to bind to the surface</b> of a white blood cell</p></li><li><p>White all heavy chains are <b>coded for by the same gene</b>, post-transcriptional modification determines whether or not this <b>extra section of protein</b> is present in the heavy chain of an antibody</p></li><li><p><b>Post transcriptional modification</b> mechanisms include</p><ul><li><p>Splicing</p></li><li><p>Alternative splicing</p></li></ul></li></ul><h4 id="splicing">Splicing</h4><ul><li><p>Polypeptides are made during the process of protein synthesis, during which the DNA base code is <span class="popovers" data-content="Formation of messenger RNA molecules from the DNA that makes up a particular gene. It is the first stage of protein synthesis." data-title="Transcription" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">transcribed</span> and <span class="popovers" data-content="The latter part of protein synthesis when the mRNA is used as template to which complementary tRNA molecules attach and the amino acids link to form a polypeptide." data-title="Translation" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">translated</span></p></li><li><p>The DNA code within eukaryotic cells contains many <b>non-coding sections</b></p></li><li><p>Non-coding DNA can be found within genes; these sections are called <b>introns, </b>while<b> </b>sections of coding DNA are called <b>exons</b></p></li><li><p>During transcription eukaryotic cells transcribe both introns and exons to produce<b> pre-mRNA </b>molecules</p></li><li><p>Before the pre-mRNA exits the nucleus, a process called <b>splicing</b> occurs</p><ul><li><p>The non-coding intron sections are removed</p></li><li><p>The coding exon sections are joined together</p></li><li><p>The resulting mRNA molecule contains <b>only the coding sequences</b> of the gene</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Since these modifications are made after transcription occurred, they are called <b>post-transcriptional modifications</b></p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Splicing of pre-mRNA 1" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="666" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-1.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Splicing of pre-mRNA 2" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="472" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-2.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/08/Splicing-of-pre-mRNA-2.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021